2. But this is not all; if we mark, we may ſee his
greateſt favour, his Goſpel comming among us: the Bible, before only known in the Church-Volume, hath by the meanes of worthy Sir Tho. Middleton been tranſlated to the vulgar Volume:And now again, I hear, Mr. Cradock is procuring the New Teſtament to be printed in Welſh in a little Volume, whereby it may grow more portable & common, which may be of much uſe in ſhort time to introduce the knowledge of the Goſpel among us. In ſome places of Wales the Goſpel doth already kindle; and that (which our Countries can never too gratefully acknowledge) by the worthy and godly endeavour of Mr. Cradock; and eſpecially (which is worth our notice) it begins to ſhine in a place heretofore noted for untowardnes, called Llangerick in Mongomeryſhire, a place formerly but of very ſorry fame, but now pointed at as the Puritans & Roundheads of Wales;
Mr. Powel. Mr. Roberts and all this through the godly pains of ſome perſecuted Miniſters, reſorting thither through manifold diſcouragements and dangers.
